programme.title: Tractor Loader Gravel Driveway Building Made Easy!
programme.desc: You don't need a skid steer or bulldozer to make a new gravel driveway! Hey folks, welcome back and if you have a tractor with a loader and a bucket You can make your own gravel driveway! In today's episode I'll share with you the most cost effective way to build a lasting gravel driveway with only your tractor and the loader with a dirt bucket. Many will say that you will need more than this, such as 2" to 3" breaker run stone as a base, or road fabric as a base underneath so that your new gravel driveway will hold up. Today I will take you along, step by step, as I cut a new gravel driveway on our 'new to us' Southern Missouri Ozarks farm. I'll be using my KIOTI NS6010 hst compact tractor and the standard factory tractor loader and a dirt bucket. First I'll show you how to skim the 'soft' layer of dirt and silt and get down to the firm, virgin layer of red clay, that exists in much of the Midwest. Now if you have a softer loamy dirt, such as in a bottom field, then you may have to use a larger base layer underneath your top layer so that the new gravel driveway holds up, particularly in wet weather. Or a road fabric underneath may also be used. But if you live in clay country, and you get down to the virgin earth's clay layer and then lay your base layer WITH small 'fines' or packing material mixed in with the gravel/stone then your driveway will be fine once compacted down and the rain gets sealed out, after the base layer is established. This is the common principle with building a gravel road or driveway. Also the shape of your gravel driveway will help to repel water when it rains, but in today's driveway build I am just building this gravel driveway flat as there is not much runoff or water erosion in this spot to warrant a driveway crown, tilt or runoff ditch. Thanks for joining us today, we hope to catch you on a future video!

programme.title: HOW he transformed a DEER DESERT in ONE year
programme.desc:
Deer season just ended! Now what? Hey folks, thanks for joining us today for our Missouri/Midwest winter deer scouting/land management episode as we continue on our year round mission of deer hunting, deer land management improvements, property improvements, wildlife habitat improvements, outdoor adventures, and land improvement projects. For folks like us (Me and Pro Staffer Phil @kapperoutdoors ) we do this stuff year round to continually improve our properties for deer hunting, turkey hunting, deer habitat, turkey habitat and overall wildlife habitat improvements. Today we'll put up the DJI mini 3 pro drone while snow is on the ground and do a property tour of Pro Staffer Phil's 165 acre Southern Missouri farm. We'll talke about how his food plots did this year, his fall green micro food plots, talk about deer hunting strategy, we'll get a look at his 150" class buck that he did harvest this year, we'll talk about the missed opportunitues at multiple bigger bucks that he had this year, we'll talk about deer stand placements, deer tower strategies, deer watering hole placements, future land improvement projects, and much more! Also we'll get some beautiful scenery on a cold and snow covered January day as we get some air time with the DJI mini 3 pro drone, learn and share our passion with all of you! Thanks for joining us today, as always if you enjoyed today's video episode please hit the like button and leave us a comment, we would greatly appreciate it. We are constantly learning in life and land management and we are always willing to learn new things, learn from our mistakes and share our success' and failures with all of you to help you to improve on your own deer hunting situation, or your own land management projects, food plots, deer habitat projects, wildlife habitat projects and just getting the most out of life when it comes to your deer hunting or outdoor experiences.

programme.title: Missouri Cattle Pond resurrection project-The last trees will fall!
programme.desc:
A neglected pond is revitalized in the Ozarks. This video explores the process of restoring a pond to its former glory, showcasing techniques and strategies for a thriving ecosystem.
Join us for our latest mini series from our new 575 acre Missouri Ozark's farm as I begin to tackle the severely overgrown and unloved pond on this beautiful Missouri Ozarks property. This will take some time and effort with my Bobcat E42 R2 series mini excavator so I will tackle in sequence for a new mini series, until I get things completed. Join us for latest episode of this ongoing Pond reclamation project mini series. This summer I've been clearing all of the decades old growth and woods from around this pond (the cattle pond) and as you'll see by the size of some of these locust trees it was really overgrown! I have also repaired the blown out pond dam as this pond was completely dry and silted over when we moved in. Since then I have made a lot of progress! Today I will clear the last of the remaining trees and brush that formerly enveloped the entire pond.
